This updates the `project.items.list()` to fetch all items in a project, regardless of number. This is accomplished by a paginated query.

## What's Changed

I added `pageInfo` to the original query so we could determine whether or not additional paginated queries are necessary. This allows us to retain a single query when the project has less than 100 items, and only results in additional queries beyond 100 items, without duplicating the projectNext info fetching.

I added a test to complete coverage, but the nature of mocking the queries didn't give me too much confidence, so I ran it a few different projects locally to confirm it _really_ works. It functioned w/ projects that had less than 100 items and more than 200 items.

```
// @ts-check

import { Octokit } from "@octokit/core";
import GitHubProject from "./index.js";

async function main() {
  const octokit = new Octokit({
    auth: process.env.GITHUB_TOKEN,
  });

  const project = new GitHubProject({
    org: process.env.GITHUB_REPOSITORY.split("/")[0],
    number: Number(process.env.PROJECT_NUMBER),
    octokit,
  });

  const items = await project.items.list();
  console.log(items);
  console.log(items.length);
}

main();

```

Includes the `type` field on the project item and uses that to determine the `isDraft` status.

The GraphQL API changed so that `content: {}` when `type: "DRAFT_ISSUE"`, but our TS types still show it as `undefined` (this seems fine since then we don't need to make all content fields optional).

### Note 
We may want to consider whether `isDraft` field should exist on the ProjectItem. The following state is possible (and arguably confusing):

```
// ProjectItem
{
  type: "PULL_REQUEST",
  isDraft: false,
  content: {
    isDraft: true
  }
}
```

Since ProjectItem.isDraft is really referring to whether you're looking at a *DRAFT_ISSUE*, we could instead key based on the type. This would be a breaking change, but in a future PR we may want to consider:

```diff
type DraftItem<TFields> = {
  id: string;
-  isDraft: true;
+  type: "DRAFT_ISSUE";
  fields: TFields;
};
type NonDraftItem<TFields> = {
  id: string;
+  type: "ISSUE" | "PULL_REQUEST" | "REDACTED";
-  isDraft: false;
  fields: TFields;
  content: Issue | PullRequest;
};
```

Additionally the GQL api has updated so that `content: {}` when `type: "DRAFT_ISSUE"`. I personally prefer to keep our types as if `content` was undefined instead of being more aligned and having to optionally type all properties on `content`
